Overview

This report examines music album popularity and the ability to predict how popular albums will be. Music is such a subjective art, it is a complicated question to explore the factors that influence it; however, throughout this project, I have found some success in accurately predicting the popularity of songs with the models discussed below.

The data used for this project was gathered from Spotify about albums and their popularity from the last 100 years1. I will use a subset of this dataset to attempt to make a regression model that predicts popularity on a scale of 1 to 100, with higher numbers meaning more popular.

  • 1 This dataset can be found here on kaggle.

    • Results

    Throughout the project, I tried two different recipes (one basic and one advanced) on 6 different tuned model types for a total of 12 models. This yielded a variety of results. I assessed each models performance based on their RMSE value, with the lowest value being the best performance. We can see the models performances in Table 1. The basic recipe models are labeled KS and the advanced recipe models are labeled Adv Rec.

    Table 1: RMSE Values of all models
    Model RMSE
    KS Null 17.975565
    Adv Rec Null 17.975565
    KS Linear 16.187092
    Adv Rec Linear 15.954043
    KS Boosted Tree 12.109514
    Adv Rec Boosted Tree 12.108988
    KS Elastic Net 16.186875
    Adv Rec Elastic Net 15.953009
    KS KNN 12.021808
    Adv Rec KNN 11.958743
    KS Random Forest 9.384061
    Adv Rec Random Forest 9.385032

    As you can see in Table 1, the KS Random Forest model performed the best, so I then ran it on testing data to see how it performs with data it was not trained on. I was happy to see that it actually performed even better, as you can see in Table 2.

    Table 2: Metrics for Final Model
    Metric Estimate
    rmse 8.9217754
    mae 4.3273708
    rsq 0.7608791

    With an RMSE value even lower than before, a low MAE, and a high R squared, this model seems to have been fairly successful. The success is even more exciting when we remember how subjective music enjoyment is.

    Finally, we can visually see the model’s performance in Figure 1, which shows the predicted popularity versus the actual popularity for the testing set. You can see that the model’s biggest issue was predicting albums would be more popular than they ultimately were. I provide a full explanation for this in the final report.

    Conclusions

    Although art is subjective and difficult to boil down into numbers, there still exist interesting patterns that can be found through thorough data analysis and modeling. I think this area deserves further research, particularly into the psychology of music enjoyment and how songs become universally adored. Is it more about the song itself or the marketing of it? This is something I couldn’t explore here but I would love to dig into at a later date!
